fields.description:
Bitbucket has a feature wich helps you to let others know that you have moved your repository somewhere else.

It works like this:

# Remove repository
# Provide new address while removing

Than Bitbucket will remove the repo, but will also keep the link

{code}
    https://bitbucket.org/{USERNAME}/{PROJECT_NAME}
{code}

which will provide to the page like

{code}
    This repository has been deleted
    Our apologies, but the repository "{PROJECT_NAME}" has been deleted.
    It now lives at {NEW_REPO_ADDRESS}
{code}

And there is a problem...\\
What if I remove that "new repo"? How can I delete the "entry" from my bitbucket?\\
What if I want to move back to Bitbucket w/o changing the name of the repo?\\
(I cannot create any new repo with the old name)

Is it possible to fix it?

There is no way to correctly implement a service account on Bitbucket Cloud.

Formerly, SSH keys on team/organization account could be used for this purpose, but for some time now, the server is emitting this sort of warnings

{code}
#!python

remote: Warning!
remote: You are currently connecting with your team account.remote: This is no longer supported, so please connect using your user account.
{code}

The recommended way of providing automation seems to be using SSH Access keys, but these only allow Read-Only access, no write access.

Asking on the Atlassian Community, the only answer I got was to use my personal account as a service account, which is unsatisfactory.

Please provide SSH Access keys with read-write access on Bitbucket Cloud.

Let&#x27;s say I&#x27;m on a file page in source browser and I found the following line in it:

{code}
if (!empty($_SERVER[&#x27;HTTP_X_REQUESTED_WITH&#x27;]) && strtolower($_SERVER[&#x27;HTTP_X_REQUESTED_WITH&#x27;]) == &#x27;xmlhttprequest&#x27;) {
{code}

I&#x27;d like to know which commit introduced it. Currently my only option seems to be scrolling up to the top and going through all commits that affected this file.

I think being able to search for that piece of code within all commits of this given file would help.

Tried to make my explanation short yet meaningful, please let me know if I haven&#x27;t succeeded :) Thanks for the amazing product by the way!

I attempted to GET this REST API URL a couple of times, and I&#x27;m failing to retrieve data.

The API I&#x27;m accessing: {{https://api.bitbucket.org/1.0/repositories/atlassian/aui/branches}}

The responses I&#x27;m getting (after ~28 seconds):

{code:json}
{"type": "error", "error": {message: "Internal server error", id: "c8b2af981c74458f91359b7e1c0e9c79"}}
{"type": "error", "error": {"message": "Internal server error", "id": "9e7d334df34947198914e0fff334f492"}}
{code}

This is happening irrespective of whether I add an {{authorization:Bearer...}} header or not.
